            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="For small amounts and learning, start with a reputable self-custodial mobile wallet. Write down and securely store your seed phrase from day one. As your holdings grow, add a hardware wallet for cold storage. The key principle: start with self-custody immediately, even if you begin small. Building good habits early is more valuable than any specific app choice."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Can a hardware wallet be hacked?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Physical access attacks (side-channel analysis, fault injection, chip decapping) are theoretically possible but require sophisticated lab equipment, expertise, and physical possession of the device. Supply chain attacks &mdash; buying a tampered device from an untrusted seller &mdash; are a more practical concern. Remote hacking of a properly designed hardware wallet is essentially impossible because the device has no network interface. Always buy directly from the manufacturer and verify firmware integrity upon first setup."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Is it safe to keep crypto on an exchange?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Exchanges are frequent targets for hackers and have a documented history of collapses. Mt. Gox (2014), QuadrigaCX (2019), and FTX (2022) collectively lost billions in customer funds. While exchanges are convenient for active trading, long-term storage exposes you to counterparty risk that you cannot control or mitigate. The crypto community summarizes this as: &quot;Not your keys, not your coins.&quot;"></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>How many hardware wallets should I own?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="For a single-sig setup, one hardware wallet plus a properly stored seed phrase backup is sufficient. Having a spare device speeds up recovery if the primary device fails. For a multi-sig setup (e.g., 2-of-3), you need at least 2-3 devices, ideally from different manufacturers to avoid correlated firmware vulnerabilities. The devices should be stored in separate physical locations."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>What is a watch-only wallet?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="A watch-only wallet imports your extended public key (xpub) without any private key material. It can display your balances, generate receiving addresses, and construct unsigned transactions &mdash; but it cannot sign or spend. This is useful for monitoring balances on your phone while the signing keys stay securely on a hardware wallet. Watch-only wallets are a key component of air-gapped signing workflows."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

